  "summary": "Sourcegraph's frontend authentication and authorization chain is composed of layered HTTP middleware assembled in cmd/frontend/internal/cli/http.go (newExternalHTTPHandler). The outermost layers (first to run) handle infrastructure concerns: IP allowlist enforcement (ipallowlist), tenant resolution from hostname (multi-tenant cloud), distributed tracing (instrumentation, trace), anonymous UID tracking (session.AnonymousUIDMiddleware), and request client info extraction (requestclient). CORS and security headers are applied per-route via secureHeadersMiddleware.\n\nAuthentication credential extraction runs next, applied bottom-up (LIFO order in code): (1) HTTP Header Auth (httpheader.AuthMiddleware) for proxy-based auth where a trusted upstream proxy sets a username/email header; (2) Access Token Auth (accesstoken.AccessTokenAuthMiddleware) which accepts tokens via query param, Basic Auth, or 'Authorization: token <tok>' header — supports sudo tokens for site admins; (3) OAuth Token Auth (oauthtoken.OAuthTokenAuthMiddleware) for tokens issued by the internal IdP (Fosite-based). For the GraphQL/internal API, cookie/session auth is then checked via session.CookieMiddlewareWithCSRFSafety (CSRF-safe: only trusts cookies from trusted origins identified by Sec-Fetch-Site and Origin headers); for the App (HTML), session.CookieMiddleware is used unconditionally. Sessions are stored in Redis (gorilla/sessions + redistore).\n\nAfter credentials are extracted the actor is set in context. Auth enforcement follows: APIRequireAuthMiddleware / AppRequireAuthMiddleware / ExternalAPIRequireAuthMiddleware reject unauthenticated requests for protected routes (allowAnonymousRequest defines the exempted paths such as sign-in, webhooks, LSIF uploads). API scope enforcement (apiscope.RequireScopes) then validates that access tokens carry the required scopes (user:all or mcp scopes). Feature flags are injected (featureflag.Middleware). Finally, authz.PostAuthMiddleware enforces licensing — authenticated non-admin users are blocked if the Sourcegraph license/grant is invalid.\n\nAuthN providers register via providers.RegisterProviderFactory during Init(): builtin username/password (userpasswd), GitHub OAuth (githuboauth), GitLab OAuth (gitlaboauth), Azure DevOps OAuth (azureoauth), Bitbucket Cloud OAuth (bitbucketcloudoauth), Bitbucket Server OAuth (bitbucketserveroauth), Gerrit (gerrit), HTTP Header (httpheader), OpenID Connect (oidc), SAML 2.0 (saml), Sourcegraph Operator/SOAP (sourcegraphoperator), and Sourcegraph Accounts/SAMS (sourcegraphaccounts). Auth flow endpoints are served under /.auth/ via dedicated handlers (SOAP login/callback, SAML metadata/login/ACS/logout, OIDC login/callback, generic OAuth login/callback). The ConnectOrSignOutMiddleware on /.auth/ handles session sign-out vs account connection flows.\n\nRepository-level authorization is enforced via the authz.Provider interface (internal/authz/iface.go) implemented by 7 code-host providers: GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket Server, Bitbucket Cloud, Gerrit, Azure DevOps, and Perforce. These are instantiated by NewAuthzProviderFactory (internal/authz/providers/authz.go) which reads external service configs. Permissions are synced to the database by a background worker (cmd/worker/internal/authz/perms_syncer.go) and enforced in SQL queries via AuthzQueryConds (internal/database/permdb/repos_perm.go) which filters the repo table against the user_repo_permissions table. Sub-repository permissions (file-level ACLs) are handled via the SubRepoPermissionChecker interface. The external connect API (externalapi) uses an additional authz interceptor (externalapi/middleware/authz.go) for Connect/gRPC endpoints."
