  "summary": "Sourcegraph's frontend auth chain is assembled in newExternalHTTPHandler (cmd/frontend/internal/cli/http.go). Middleware runs outermost-first (innermost registered last in LIFO stacking). Global layers applied to every request: (1) IP allowlist (ipallowlist) blocks forbidden IPs immediately; (2) tenant resolution from hostname (multi-tenant cloud); (3) instrumentation/tracing (instrumentation.HTTPMiddleware, tracepkg.HTTPMiddleware); (4) requestclient extraction from HTTP headers; (5) anonymous UID from cookie (session.AnonymousUIDMiddleware) for analytics; (6) CORS + security headers (secureHeadersMiddleware) which also enforces origin trust.\n\nCredential extraction middleware (applied per route handler, LIFO — last line runs first): (a) httpheader.AuthMiddleware — reads a configured proxy-set header (e.g. X-Forwarded-User) and sets the actor from a trusted upstream auth proxy; (b) accesstoken.AccessTokenAuthMiddleware — validates Sourcegraph personal access tokens from query param, Basic Auth, or 'Authorization: token <tok>' header, supports sudo impersonation for site admins, attaches API scopes to context; (c) oauthtoken.OAuthTokenAuthMiddleware — validates OAuth 2.0 Bearer tokens issued by the internal Fosite-based IdP (served at /.auth/idp/oauth/*); (d) session.CookieMiddlewareWithCSRFSafety (API) or session.CookieMiddleware (App) — reads gorilla/sessions Redis-backed session cookie, enforces CSRF safety by only trusting cookies from same-origin or allow-listed CORS origins (checked via Sec-Fetch-Site header + Origin fallback).\n\nAuth enforcement: APIRequireAuthMiddleware / AppRequireAuthMiddleware / ExternalAPIRequireAuthMiddleware reject unauthenticated requests unless AllowAnonymousRequest permits the path (sign-in pages, webhooks, LSIF/SCIP upload endpoints). ConnectOrSignOutMiddleware on /.auth/ decides whether to connect an external account or sign out. apiscope.RequireScopes enforces that access tokens carry required scopes (user:all for API/App, mcp scope for MCP paths). featureflag.Middleware adds feature flags to context. authz.PostAuthMiddleware enforces license validity — blocks non-admin authenticated users when the Sourcegraph license/grant is invalid.\n\nAuth provider registration: auth.Init() (cmd/frontend/internal/auth/init.go) initialises 12 providers, each calling providers.RegisterProviderFactory: builtin username/password (userpasswd), GitHub OAuth (githuboauth), GitLab OAuth (gitlaboauth), Azure DevOps OAuth (azureoauth), Bitbucket Cloud OAuth (bitbucketcloudoauth), Bitbucket Server OAuth (bitbucketserveroauth), Gerrit (gerrit), HTTP Header proxy (httpheader), OpenID Connect (oidc), SAML 2.0 (saml), Sourcegraph Operator/SOAP (sourcegraphoperator), and Sourcegraph Accounts/SAMS (sourcegraphaccounts). Auth flow endpoints are mounted at /.auth/ and dispatch to typed handlers (SOAP login+callback, SAML metadata/login/ACS/logout, OIDC login/callback, generic OAuth login/callback, authvalidation). Sessions are created/updated in these callbacks and stored in Redis.\n\nRepository-level authorization uses the authz.Provider interface (internal/authz/iface.go) with methods FetchUserPerms, FetchRepoPerms, and FetchAccount. Seven code-host authz providers are instantiated by NewAuthzProviderFactory (internal/authz/providers/authz.go): GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket Server, Bitbucket Cloud, Gerrit, Azure DevOps, and Perforce. Permissions are synced to the database by a background worker (cmd/worker/internal/authz/perms_syncer.go) and enforced in SQL via AuthzQueryConds (internal/database/permdb/repos_perm.go) which joins against the user_repo_permissions table. Sub-repository file-level permissions are gated via SubRepoPermissionChecker (internal/authz/sub_repo_perms.go). The external Connect/gRPC API has an additional per-method authz interceptor (externalapi/middleware/authz.go) that checks proto method options against the actor's roles."
